Introduction¶

  • This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row. I will try by data which are available to answer that question:
  • #### "What may affect the patient's attendance of the appointment?".

Adding a column 'Day_of_Schedule' for show day of week for 'ScheduledDay',¶

to see if no show cases are occur on a specific day or days during the week?¶

In [9]:
f = lambda x: datetime.strptime(x, '%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ')
df.ScheduledDay = df.ScheduledDay.apply(f)
df.AppointmentDay = df.AppointmentDay.apply(f)
In [10]:

df['Day_of_Appointment']=df['AppointmentDay'].dt.day_name()

Limitation¶

There is no data on the level of education and work that shows a cultural and intellectual background about the patient and that might explain the study we are dealing with.¶

All the variables in the patient database do not have a strong effect that helps predict whether the patient will go to his appointment or not.¶

Conclusions¶

Attendance to non-attendance rate is 79.81 % to 20.19 %.¶

After clarifying the effect of variables on attendance or not, it became clear that when explaining each variable, the percentage of non-attendance ranged from 20% to 25%, which is close to the original percentage of non-attendance, which is 20.19%, and thus there is no overwhelming reason to explain non-attendance among the majority of patients who did not attend.¶

After analysis dataset i found that all variables have the same efect on No-show patients, no specific reason found to determine if patient will be no-show or not.¶

there is an entry is incorrect that Age value is -1.¶

* notes:¶

This is what was shown to us through these variables, and it can be proven otherwise from the point of view of another study.¶
